<br>
The simple question broke the high priest from his reverie.  He blinked in the hot sun and gazed at his daughter who stood in front of him, hot and sweaty from practice in the arena.  He blinked again and then smiled at the pretty half-elf standing in front of him.<br>
<br>
“I was just thinking how alike your mother you are.”<br>
<br>
Delaine laughed out loud.  “Oh, father!  Like mother?  Look at me!  I am a warrior!  I’m all dirty and hot and sweaty.  Can you ever imagine mother lifting a sword?  Much less get hot and sweaty?”<br>
<br>
Emmedain’s wayward thoughts led him to think of the times that Arawayne was hot and sweaty.  He was thinking much too much of her these days.  Ever since he had discovered that he had a daughter.  With practiced discipline, he put his thoughts of the past away and forced himself into the present.  He chuckled, joining in his daughter’s laugher.<br>
<br>
“Well, in her youth, your mother was known to wield a staff now and again, with grace and ferocity.  Many a time it was at me, however, when she was threatening me…”<br>
<br>
Delaine laughed again, and then thrust out her hand at her father.  “Help me father, I have a boo-boo.”<br>
<br>
The flashback was intense this time.  “Arawyne…”<br>
<br>
“Father?”<br>
<br>
Emmedain visibly shook himself as he took his daughter’s hand.  He came when he could nowadays, when the young warriors trained in the arena, to offer his aid in healing accidental hurts and cuts.  Her sparing opponent had gotten through her guard and slashed the back of her forearm.  He frowned as he examined it.  It was an ugly gash, but not deep.  Murmuring a spell of cleansing, then one of healing, he nodded with satisfaction as the flesh knitted.<br>
<br>
Delaine chuckled as the potent magics flowed over her flesh.  The healing spell her father had cast was one that healed both flesh and soul.  “Thank you, father, but a minor healing would have been enough.”<br>
<br>
Emmedain smiled and patted his daughter’s hand.  “Your mother said that to me once, but like I told her then, and I’ll tell you now.  I like to see you whole and it takes little from me to use a superior heal.  You do look like your mother, you know.”<br>
<br>
Delaine made a face.  “She’s beautiful.  All elfin grace and charm, and that beautiful white blonde hair…”<br>
<br>
Emmedain grinned and interrupted his daughter.  “I do know how your mother looks, and you have the look of her about you.  Your smile, the way you toss your head… and hey… don’t you like the strawberry blonde hair you got because of me?”<br>
<br>
Delaine made another face and grabbed her short hair in her hands.  “It’s carrot!  You have this dark red hair that I would die for… mother has this gorgeous blonde, and I get carrot!”<br>
<br>
Emmedain laughed now.  “Enough.  Your head would get too large for your helm if I always praised you.”<br>
<br>
“But..”<br>
<br>
“Look at me, Lainie…”  Emmedain commanded sternly.  “You are a beautiful young woman.  You are different than the high-elf that your mother is, you are different than the human that I am.  Indeed you have the best of both worlds.  Now stop thinking about your looks and concentrate on your sword work or you will never attain the sword circle you wish.”<br>
<br>
Delaine cocked her head at her father then smiled.  The mischievous little smile that Emmedain recognized.  It was the smile that Arawyne would give him, just before she suggested something outrageous or dangerous.  He was on his guard before his daughter even asked.<br>
<br>
“Well, would you hunt goblins with me?  A few more goblin war beads as trophies would not be amiss to the Temple of Life, and I am close to finishing my second tier trials.”<br>
<br>
Emmedain considered his daughter’s request and her eager face.  She was indeed close.  Well, a little help now would not be amiss.  He would help her attain her second tier rank.  “Very well.  I do have the time today, after all.”<br>
<br>
“Yay!”<br>
<br>
Delaine cheered and danced off to store her practice weapons at her foster parents’ house and don her hunting gear.  Emmedain watched her run off indulgently and examined his pouches.  As usual, they were full of reagents for his spells, but none for the minor spells he would use for his daughter this day.  Well, he would purchase a few pieces of Amber and provide a minor magical shield.  From experience, he knew that a greater shield made her cocky and careless.<br>
