<br>
“Well, she has no healing spells to protect me with, so she gave me the best armor she could buy.”<br>
<br>
Luckily, she didn’t, thought Emmedain as they rode from the city toward the goblin mines at the foothills of the Karana Pass.  Delaine was dressed in a full suit of crafted plate armor, Elven craftsmenship for sure, but not the finest, nor was it a suit of dragon mail.  Still, it was better than any that a second or even third tier warrior could afford.  Delaine needed to hone her skills, not depend on armor to protect her.<br>
<br>
“And the horse?”<br>
<br>
Delaine coughed and blushed.  “Well, I pay for his stabling and keep…”<br>
<br>
Emmedain snorted.  “She gifted you with an elfin steed, daughter.  Don’t try to hoodwink me, Lainie.  Elfin horses need no food and keep.  You summon them when you require their aid and dismiss them when you are done.”<br>
<br>
“Well… actually… grandmother did.  With Silvermist, I can actually ride the feyways to Felwithe and visit.  Ma crafted the saddle and Da did the metalwork of course.  Mine was the first saddle Ma did and she liked them well enough that she has started to sell them.”<br>
<br>
Delaine chattered on as they reached the forest of Mervamel, where perforce, they had to ride in single file and silence and attention to their surroundings would serve them better.  The verdant forest began to change as they neared the goblin mines.  The trees and bushes were stunted and deformed from the poisoning of the land caused by the dregs of goblin mining.  Emmedain had made his daughter lead and now she chose a small clearing where they would stage.  He prepared a spell of protection.  <br>
<br>
Delaine grinned as she felt her father’s magics flow over her.  This would be a piece of cake.  She dismounted and removing her packs and saddle from his back, bade her steed return to his lands.<br>
<br>
Emmedain frowned as his daughter prepared herself.  “No shield?”<br>
<br>
“No.  I can deal more damage with two-sword, and besides… I need the two-sword practice.”<br>
<br>
“That’s what the arena is for.”<br>
<br>
“Not the same.”<br>
<br>
Emmedain was forced to agree.  <br>
<br>
“Will you pull for me?”<br>
<br>
Emmedain raised an eyebrow.  He patted the saddlebag on his horse and withdrew a book.<br>
<br>
“I am here to help you.  Not feed you like a baby.”<br>
<br>
Delaine stuck her tongue out at her father mischievously then placed her helm on her head, fastening it securely.  Unwrapping her bow, she strung it carefully and nocked an arrow on it.<br>
<br>
“Your mother?”  The comment was dry.<br>
<br>
Delaine grinned.  “Uncle Tarube made it.”<br>
<br>
“Uncle?”<br>
<br>
“He is now!”  was the enthusiastic response.<br>
<br>
Emmedian reached out a hand silently and Delaine removed the arrow and handed her bow to her father. Delaine was picking up an extended family of adoptive aunts and uncles, it seemed.  There were few children among his set.  Since his friends had realized that she was his daughter, she often found herself the recipient of their hand-me-downs.  Thank Marr that most were too powerful for her to wield and sat in the safety of the Freeport bank’s stronghold.<br>
<br>
“He saw me at archery practice when he last passed through Freeport.  I was still using a short bow so he gave me this one.”<br>
<br>
Emmedain ran his hands over the bow.  Beautiful craftsmanship as could be expected from a Master Bowyer.  It gleamed with a magic aura.  Indeed.  It was his best of easily acquired mundane materials.  <br>
<br>
“The arrows?”<br>
<br>
“Oh!  I made them myself!”<br>
<br>
She handed them to him proudly.  Emmedain examined her handiwork.  The arrows were well made if still a little crude.  “Very well.  Don’t bring back the entire goblin horde.  I don’t feel like doing a resurrection today.”<br>
<br>
Delaine laughed, but nodded and moved carefully toward the mouth of the goblin mines.  Ahhh… good.  It was lightly guarded as usual.  The goblins were more interested in mining the land than protecting their own.  She often wondered if there were goblin mothers who worried about their children.  Delaine watched and gauged the distance.  Goblin miners moved in and out of the mines.  Two guards stood watch at the entrance, and one patrolled the perimeter.  Oh!  Her heart leapt.  A goblin guard captain!  She could tell by the colorful war beads it wore.  The war beads off the guard captain were worth more in prestige and points towards her competence trials than ordinary war beads.  She would never attempt a goblin guard captain alone.  It would be certain death.   With a hunting party of her level and status, maybe… but with her father…<br>
<br>
She drew the bow.  The captain walked closer to her then paused.  If she did this right, he would come charging over without alerting the other guards.  The goblins were stupid that way.  When angered or hurt, they had no thought but to hurt in return.<br>
<br>
She loosed the arrow.  Yes!  It flew true, piercing the goblin’s hard hide.  It howled in pain and looked around.  Deliberately, she stood and rustled the bushes.  The goblin squealed in rage and charged.  She grinned.  The other guards had merely looked up in the guard captain’s direction and had slumped back down in boredom.  Turning tail, she ran back to the clearing where her father would be reading his book.  Slinging the bow across her body as she ran, she unsheathed her swords in readiness.<br>
<br>
“Uhh…”  The blow of magic struck her hard.  It felt like a hundred flaming knives in her.  Then she felt the warm glow of a healing spell and grinned.  Spinning to face the enraged goblin, she yelled to her father.  “Magic protection, father, please!  Spell caster!”<br>
<br>
Emmedain gauged the strength of the prey his daughter had selected and cast a spell of magic protection on her.  He nodded.  He had known it.  She was too cocksure with him along for protection.  The minor spells he had chosen to shield her with would offer her some protection but not make her invulnerable to hurt.  However, his healing magic would close what wounds she took.<br>
<br>
This would be a long and savage fight Delaine realized.  The goblin’s hide was tough and his magics were strong.  Another blow of magic struck her and she gasped at the pain.<br>
<br>
“Bash, Lae, interrupt his magic.”<br>
<br>
Delaine gritted her teeth and wondered if that was what provoked her mother’s temper often.  He damn well knew she had not brought a shield.  Yes, she should have.  She would have switched it out with her off hand sword.  The goblin caught her a good blow and she gasped at the pain.  Damn… what protective shields had her father granted her?  Definitely not his best.  She felt the healing spell fade then strengthen.  He was renewing the healing spell.  At least she would not be seriously injured today or worse… die and have to suffer resurrection and the long recovery from that!<br>
<br>
“Dodge, Lae.  Parry.  Got to keep those skills up.”<br>
<br>
Delaine doubled her efforts.  Ha!  Piece of cake… father was making her work!  She swore as the goblin readied another spell.  She had to strike him hard enough to interrupt it and that was where the shield came in.  She could use the weight of her body, not just the strength of her arm to bash her opponent with.  The explosion of magic at close range made her ears ring, but she was not hurt.  Instead, the goblin stood motionless.  She paused.  Her father had stunned it.<br>
<br>
“I have a shield you could borrow.”<br>
<br>
Delaine turned at her father’s mild words.  He stood there, holding out a shield emblazoned with a sinuous gold dragon.<br>
<br>
“Wow!”  She marveled at the shield her father was holding out to her.  That was a shield given by the dragons only to those they deemed worthy!  She quickly loosed the sword from her off hand and took it from him, sliding her arm into the holding straps.<br>
<br>
“I want it back.”<br>
<br>
“Awww… father…”<br>
<br>
“Goblin’s waking up.”<br>
<br>
There was no more time for talk.  Delaine spun and bashed her prey hard.  It stunned him and interrupted his spell.  She hooted with glee and swung her sword with renewed vigor.<br>
<br>
Emmedain shook his head.  The warrior’s way was definitely for her.  Who would have thought that he and Arawyne could have spawned such a blood-thirsty little daughter.  Goblin guards were stupid and chosen only for their ability to fight and maim.  They did not run but fought to the death.  He renewed the powerful healing spell on his daughter, then turned back to his book.  The spell would take care of any hurts she received.<br>
<br>
In the despoiled forest, no birds sang.  Not even the raven, which often was a harbinger of evil.  Emmedain looked up from his book thoughtfully.  He leaned back against a tree and watched his daughter fight.  One could hear the chittering of a squirrel or bark of a fox sometimes but even the animals kept away.  It was quiet now, but for the thud of steel against goblin hide, the explosion of offensive magic, and the cries of the combatants; the goblin’s squeals of rage and a grunt now and again from Delaine.  She had been successful in thwarting most of the goblin’s magical attacks.  The goblin had lost the use of one arm and noxious ochres were oozing from multiple wounds.  It would not be long now and none too soon.  He had renewed the spell of healing three times, and he could see that Delaine was tiring.<br>
