<br>
Delaine saw the opening and thrust her sword hard.  Yes!  It pierced the hide weakened by the many cuts she had inflicted on it and sank into the goblins chest.  With a final gurgle of frustrated rage, it slowly toppled over and lay still.  Delaine sank to a knee beside the corpse, panting.  Thank the Goddess of Love!  It was dead.  She could feel the shield of magic protection fading and the healing spell close the last of her wounds and itself fade.<br>
<br>
“Well done, daughter.”<br>
<br>
Delaine looked up and made a face at her father.  He could have given her a little more help.<br>
<br>
“Want a zing?”<br>
<br>
“Yes, please.”  She gasped the words.  “Oh yes…  please, father.  Before I fall over.”<br>
<br>
Emmedain grinned and granted his daughter her strength and stamina back.  Delaine let herself collapse flat on her back as she let the magic “zing” through her veins, replenishing her energy and stamina.<br>
<br>
“Oh bliss!”<br>
<br>
The high priest chuckled and opened his saddlebags again.<br>
<br>
“Sit up, Lainie.  Here.”<br>
<br>
Delaine sat up as bade, and drunk lustily from the water skin her father handed her.<br>
<br>
“Oh… Mmmm!  Yum!  Pardina’s Greater Constitutional.”<br>
<br>
Emmedain nodded.  “Grants you energy and strength.”<br>
<br>
“Aye.”<br>
<br>
It was also too expensive a drink for her to afford with any sort of regularity.  Delaine rolled onto her knees and taking her dagger cut the war beads from the goblin’s neck.  The corpse was beginning to smolder.  <br>
<br>
“Urgh!”<br>
<br>
“It will immolate.  It was a fire mage.”<br>
<br>
“Wow.”<br>
<br>
Delaine stared as the corpse burned until nothing was left but ashes and a stink in the air.<br>
<br>
“Maybe I should pull more of these.”  She grinned at her father.  “No corpses to bury.”<br>
<br>
Emmedain rolled his eyes.  “Why don’t you pull something a little easier?  As I recall, miners as well as guards wear war beads.  Won’t two sets of goblin war beads be equal to one of the goblin captain’s beads?  Only the captains are spell casters.  It will also go faster.”<br>
<br>
“Yes, father.”<br>
<br>
Emmedain looked at his daughter suspiciously.   Her eyes were bright with excitement as she looked forward to the next kill.  He had two choices here.  Given his daughter’s knowledge that he would not let her die, she would probably pick the hardest prey she could, if only for the challenge.  Given his promise to help her attain the last sets of beads she needed to finish her second tier trials, he could either draw for her or resign himself to spending the rest of the afternoon waiting as she finished off each goblin.  He sighed and put away his book.  Removing his mace from his belt he held out his other hand for his shield.<br>
<br>
“I’ll pull.”<br>
